  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Living with Dignity: Sexual and Gender Based Violence and Sexual Exploitation and Harassment Prevention in the Mining Sector</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Phase 1 of the research project will involve 2 key target groups within the Amandelbult mining community. Key informant interviews (KIIs) as well as focus group discussions (FGDs) will be held with relevant Anglo American staff who would be involved in SGBV/SEA response (e.g. Social Performance, Human Resources, Protection Services, Health and Safety), a representative cross-section of workers from the Amandelbult mines and service providers in the community, and service providers working in the community who respond to possible cases of SGBV/SEA. These will include:

-	Human resources
-	Social performance and community engagement 
-	Internal and external grievances mechanisms
-	Employee assistance
-	Staff health care providers 
-	Mine-run hospitals for communities
-	Community health and social welfare providers
-	Mine security
-	Local police force
-	Local NGOs (e.g. women?s organisations, domestic violence shelters)
-	Individuals who may have received information on individual cases

Particular attention will also be paid to those working with persons living with disabilities (including work-related ones) and their respective vulnerabilities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This formative research will be qualitative in nature and will seek to determine the current state regarding experiences of SGBV/SEA as well as sexual harassment in the workplace, at home and in the affected community as well as of grievance/referral mechanisms. The research will look at these issues comprehensively, examining the experiences of women, men, girls, boys, and those with other gender identities. 

The aim of the research is not to name and shame anyone, but to identify what, broadly speaking, the nature and scale of the problem is and to improve the response to and prevention of SEA and GBV within Anglo American?s internal system and mining communities by strengthening community capacities to identify, respond to and prevent the perpetuation of SGBV/SEA through social norms.
-	Identify what systems are in place; 
-	Review how these works; 
-	Identify what possible gaps might exist and what emerging best practices can be identified.</narrative>
  </description>
